="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Encourage patient to discuss his concerns with you, including issues of death and dying that he might wish to discuss</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></response></openquestion></event><event id="117941072810925" title="Home Visit 3"><openquestion id="117941073550026" title="" status=""><question><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">What new problems would you put on the problem list?</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></question><response><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Any of the following entries on the problem list would be acceptable:</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">No new problems or</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Acute grief</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Not all clinicians would put acute grief on a problem list since it is a normal reaction. Others would do so because the patient needs to be monitored to be sure the grieving process doesn&apos;t turn into something more pathological. Whether it should be listed on a problem list is a matter of personal choice.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></response></openquestion><openquestion id="117941073735927" status=""><question><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">What learning objectives do you have?</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></question><response><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Be sure that the following learning objectives are also included on your list.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Long-term care facilities: structure, organization, function, financing</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></response></openquestion><openquestion id="117941073845328" status=""><question><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">After investigating your learning objectives, complete a management plan for Mr. Marlboro.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></question><response><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Your management plan should have included the following:</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Arrange admission to a long-term care facility</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></response></openquestion></event><event id="117941078670329" title="Nursing Home Visit 1"><openquestion id="117941079340630" title="" status=""><question><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">What new problems would you put on the problem list?</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></question><response><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Any of the following entries on the problem list would be acceptable:</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Angina pectoris (or at your level of training, you might feel confident only in stating that the patient has chest pain)</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">See the next page to learn more about the clinical presentation of chest pain due to cardiac ischemia </FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></response></openquestion><data id="12107192469484455" title=""><content><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<img alt="" src="Clin present MI2.jpg" width="" height=""/>]]></p></xhtml></content></data><openquestion id="117941079456231" title="" status=""><question><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">What learning objectives do you have?</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></question><response><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Be sure that the following learning objectives are also included on your list.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Pathophysiology of angina pectoris</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Pathology of atherosclerotic heart disease</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Pharmacology of anti-anginal drugs (e.g., nitrates, beta-adrenergic blockers, calcium channel blockers)<FONT KERNING="1"> </FONT></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></response></openquestion><openquestion id="117941079567132" title="" status=""><question><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">After investigating your learning objectives, complete a management plan for Mr. Marlboro.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></question><response><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Your management plan should have included the following:</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Obtain an electrocardiogram</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Prescribe a long-acting nitrate (e.g., isosorbide dinitrate) during the day to prevent anginal attacks.  Care should be taken if a decision is made to prescribe beta-adrenergic blockers because of pulmonary disease.</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Begin daily aspirin therapy, 325 mg. </FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">A thallium stress test might be considered.</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></response></openquestion></event><event id="117941085573433" title="Emergency Room Visit 2"><openquestion id="117941086164034" title="" status=""><question><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">What new problems would you put on the problem list?</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></question><response><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Any of the following entries on the problem list would be acceptable:</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Acute anterior myocardial infarction</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Congestive heart failure would also be an acceptable alternative problem formulation</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">See the next page for an explanation of how serum markers of acute MI can help in the rapid diagnosis of the problem.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></response></openquestion><data id="12108112186694231" title="Serum markers of myocardial infarction"><content><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Mr. Marlboro&apos;s ECG was typical of acute myocardial infarction. The diagnosis is supported by another finding--the patterns of myocardial-specific enzymes or proteins released into the circulation from the damaged myocardial cells. Normally, small amounts of these enzymes or proteins leak into the blood, but in MI these levels are grossly elevated. The timing and levels of these enzymes are then indicative of the onset and extent of the infarct.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Like the ECGs, these laboratory tests should be done in all cases with suspected acute myocardial infarction. <I>Troponin T is a particularly sensitive and specific marker of cardiac myocyte necrosis and may be raised when the ECG is normal. CK-MB is also useful in the diagnosis of acute MI, but its use is decreasing as more hospitals are recognizing the added value of troponin, which gives prognostic as well as diagnostic information.</I></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><img alt="" src="serum_markers_of_mi_v2.swf" width="" height=""/>]]></p></xhtml></content></data><openquestion id="117941086273435" title="" status=""><question><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">What learning objectives do you have?</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></question><response><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Be sure that the following learning objectives are also included on your list.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Pathophysiology of myocardial infarction</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Pathology of myocardial ischemia and infarction </FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Pharmacology of tPA, lidocaine, nitroglycerine</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></response></openquestion><openquestion id="117941086403136" title="" status=""><question><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">After investigating your learning objectives, complete a management plan for Mr. Marlboro.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></p></xhtml></question><response><xhtml><p><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Your management plan should have included the following:</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Have the patient admitted to a coronary care unit </FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Immediate and early drug treatment of acute myocardial infarction</B></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Restoring blood flow in the occluded artery by angioplasty or thrombolysis reduces mortality in ST-elevation MI. Speed is of the essence for best results.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">If primary angioplasty is available, the first priority is to transfer the patient to the cardiac catheter laboratory with a view to early angiography and stenting in order to re-establish the coronary flow in the affected artery.  During the transfer procedure the following should be administered:</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>IV access</I> â for early administration of drugs or fluids</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>Aspirin</I> (chewed) and <I>clopidogrel </I>(orally) â inhibits platelet aggregation</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>Opiate analgesic</I> â IV to relieve pain and anxiety</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>Anti-emetic</I> â nausea/vomiting common after MI and administration of opiates</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>Oxygen</I> (by nasal catheter) â in an attempt to improve the oxygen delivery to the myocardium</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>Thrombolysis</I> â to âdissolveâ coronary artery thrombus and restore coronary blood flow and improve myocardial viability (only required if primary angioplasty cannot be delivred within ninety minutes of diagnosis.  Otherwise the patient shoud have angioplasty without pretreatment with thrombolysis)</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>Trinitroglycerine</I> â if BP &gt; 90 mmHg</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>Beta-blocker </I>â to reduce heart rate, force of contraction and pain</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>ACE inhibitor </I>â to lower blood pressure and to improve ejection fraction and endothelial function</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I>Statin</I> â to stabilise coronary plaque and reduce cholesterol.</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><I></I></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Indications for thrombolysis in acute myocardial infarction</B></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B></B></FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Chest pain greater than 20 minutes and less than 12 hours</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">ST-segment elevation or left bundle branch block</FONT></LI></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><LI><FONT FACE="Arial Unicode MS,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="12" COLOR="#0B333C" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Primary angiopplasty catheter laboratory unavailable (within 90 minutes of diagnosis) or patient refuses</FONT></LI></TEXTFOR